        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/37107",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Can you please elaborate?  What elements in the index.php and\/or .htaccess are not compatible?\r\n\r\n-ralph",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-12-21T12:18:52.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-12-21T12:18:52.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/37139",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=davmor",
                        "name": "davmor",
                        "displayName": "David Moring",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Good catch, my mistake.  Under suPHP, the system vars set via the .htaccess file (ie: SetEnv APPLICATION_ENV production) do not get transferred to the executing PHP environment.\r\n\r\nI spent some time looking around, it seems that suPHP does not have a way to transfer in environment variables from .htaccess -- maybe someone deeper than I in suPHP has a way.\r\n\r\nSo one solution is to hack the index.php script that is produced by Zend Tool, but that seems inelegant, given how well the rest of Zend_Tool providers work in a staged development methodology.\r\n\r\nMaybe a better approach would be to have the application provider add a line that looks for a site specific config file that can set the environment vars (and other stuff if needed).  Maybe even use a test to see if APPLICATION_ENV is empty before sourcing the site specific file, to increase performance.  This seems to be a design kind of decision, best made by you guys.\r\n\r\nHope this helps...\r\n\r\n\r\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=davmor",
                        "name": "davmor",
                        "displayName": "David Moring",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-12-22T09:24:52.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-12-22T09:24:52.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/42635",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "How is it incompatible? Can you provide a suggestion or notes to the specific inconsistency?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
